struct PendingDependency {
    from_file_id: i64,
    dep_path: PathBuf,
}

fn index(&mut self) -> Result<IndexStats> {
    let files = self.discover_files()?;
    let mut pending: Vec<PendingDependency> = Vec::new();

    // First pass: index all files, queue failed dependencies
    for file in &files {
        self.index_file_atomic(file, &mut pending)?;
    }

    // Resolution passes: retry pending until stable
    let mut prev_count = pending.len() + 1;
    while !pending.is_empty() && pending.len() < prev_count {
        prev_count = pending.len();
        pending = self.resolve_pending(pending)?;
    }

    // Log remaining unresolved
    for p in &pending {
        debug!(from_file = p.from_file_id, dep = %p.dep_path.display(), 
               "Dependency unresolved after all passes");
    }

    Ok(stats)
}
```

description:
tethys's `resolver::resolve_super_path` interprets `super::X` from a file at `src/parent/child.rs` as a filesystem grandparent walk: `current_file.parent().parent()` then joins X, reaching `src/X.rs`. Rust's actual semantics: `super::X` from `mod parent::child` refers to `crate::parent::X`, which lives at `src/parent/X.rs` (or methods on the parent module file).

Concrete example, surfaced during rivets-044i (PR #74):

  src/lib.rs       -> mod parent;
  src/parent.rs    -> mod child; pub mod sibling;
  src/parent/child.rs:
      pub fn entry() {
          super::sibling::foo();   // Rust: src/parent/sibling.rs ; tethys: src/sibling.rs
      }

The new `self_and_super_paths_resolve_via_as_written` test in pass2_qualified_paths.rs documents this divergence (fixture lays sibling at the location tethys's resolver expects) but doesn't fix it.

Impact: any qualified ref using `super::X::method()` style from a depth-2+ file resolves to the wrong file via the qualified_module_fallback path (or fails to resolve at all if the wrong-level file doesn't exist). The use-statement form `use super::X;` goes through a different code path (Pass-2 explicit imports) and may have the same issue — needs verification.

Surfaced by claude-code-review #4 on PR #74 during round-3 review-feedback assessment, with the explicit suggestion to file a tracker entry rather than leave the divergence documented-only.

